Macedonians will vote on the referendum if they want to change the name of the country
On Sunday, Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum if they wanted the country's name to be changed to the "North Macedonia Republic", a change that would resolve an old dispute with Greece for a decade, which opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which comprises a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighbouring country represents a claim on its territory and opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June with regard to the new name proposed, but opposition nationalists argue that this change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority population in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov said that he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign had doubted the presence to vote, and that the minimum limit of 50% needed for the validation of the referendum might not be reached.
The question on the referendum ballot will be: "Do you agree with EU and NATO accession, accepting the agreement with Greece?".
Supporters of name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say that it is a price to be paid by Macedonia, one of the countries resulting from the breakup of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted in entities such as the EU and NATO.
"I am here today to vote for the future of the country, so that young people in Macedonia will live free under the umbrella of the European Union, because this means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79 years old, at Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, many members of parliament have said that they will respect the outcome of the vote in order to make it decisive.
For the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum is required in parliament.
The State Electoral Commission said no irregularities were reported until 13:00.
However, the participation was only 16%, compared to 34% at the last parliamentary elections in 2016 when 66% of the people with voting rights voted.
"I came to the vote for my children and our place in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, aged 62, a voter from Skopje, the capital of the country.
On 30 September 2018, Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica, and their son, Dushko, voted for the referendum on the change of Macedonian name, which will allow them to join NATO and enter the European Union.
In front of the Skopje parliament, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small scene of size and drew seats in front of the high tents of those who would boycott the referendum.
"We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with the top, not the back door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia and become part of the Euro-Asian Union."
Prime Minister Zaev said NATO membership will bring so much needed investments to Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of more than 20%.
"I believe that most will be in favour of changing names, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of joining NATO and the EU," Zaev said after he voted.
He said that a result in the change of name would be “confirming our future”.
According to a survey published last month by the Institute for Policy Research, between 30% and 43% of the citizens with voting rights will participate in the referendum, under the number of participants required.
According to another poll conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote in favour of change.
For the referendum to be valid, the vote must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first serious blow to the pro-vestic government policy since the takeover of the government in May last year.
