HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of Chinese citizens suffering from HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by this disease in China, the officials say.
About 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases were sexually transmitted, unlike those of the past.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
But the number of people who contracted HIV in this way was almost zero, Chinese health officials say at a conference in Yunnan Province.
From one year to another, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is an acute problem in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is considered to be widespread.
Because of the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men will eventually get married to a woman.
Many cases of transmission of diseases stem from inadequate sexual protection measures in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to drugs against HIV as part of its efforts to solve the problem.
