This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grassland, and which is the best way to maintain forest forests for bats and other associated species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and throughout Britain have fallen considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by construction and development work that affects the nests, as well as habitat loss.
And wind turbines and public lighting are risks, as are the traps for flies and some chemical treatments for construction materials, but also attacks on domestic cats.
Actually, bats aren't blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching the prey.
They use a sophisticated echo technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight route.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, thinks very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who regularly conduct studies, control the nests and sometimes carry out rescue missions.
The organization created even the first and only reservation of bats in Scotland, on the estate Thrave in Dumfries and Galloway, where there are eight of ten species of bats in Scotland.
