It's been a decade since the last trial of a case of capital punishment in New York's Southern District.
The street, Khalid Barnes, was accused of killing two drug dealers, but finally he was sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last capital punishment applied in a federal case in New York took place in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, two husbands executed after being convicted of conspiracy to commit the act of spying for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The Rosenberg wives were executed on the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
