How can it be beneficial for Beijing's trade war between the United States and China?
Salves that announced the start of the trade war between the United States and China were absurd and, while there seems to be a long way to end it, disputes between the two countries could be beneficial for long-term Beijing, experts say.
Donald Trump, President of the United States, issued the first warning earlier this year by imposing taxes on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most important escalation took place this week with new taxes, which affected products worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), actually applying taxes for half of all the goods in China arriving in the United States.
Beijing took revenge every time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10 per cent for US products worth 60 billion dollars.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the second largest economy of the world will take a step back in the near future.
In order for Washington to withdraw, China must agree with its demands, but publicly surrendering to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, President of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, US trade war pressures could positively support China in the long term, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision made in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would actually be more dangerous than what has been planned so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher who is focusing on Asia at the Center for a New American Security (Center for New American Security), an expert group.
