The latest report of the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general decrease in the concentrations of the Red Sea for certain areas of the Tampa Gulf.
According to the Commission, ununiform conditions of inflorescence are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
This inflorescence of the red sea extends over an area of the coast of approximately 210 km, from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
Pets can be found about 16 km off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The Red Sea was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations found in or off Pinellas County have been reported last week, as well as low concentrations up to high in Hillsborough County, background concentrations up to high in Manatee County, background concentrations up to high in or off Sarasota County, background concentrations up to medium in Charlotte County, background concentrations up to high in Lee County and across it and low concentrations in Collier County.
Irritations of respiratory pathways continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of irritation of respiratory pathways in North-West American state Florida have been reported in the last week.
